{
  "The ACL (anterior cruciate ligament) prevents:": "",
  "Lateral knee movement only": "",
  "Posterior knee movement only": "",
  "Anterior (forward) translation of the tibia relative to the femur": "",
  "Hip rotation": "",
  "The anterior cruciate ligament runs diagonally inside the knee joint and is the primary restraint against anterior tibial translation, preventing the tibia from sliding forward relative to the femur during activities like cutting, pivoting, and landing.": "",
  "The rotator cuff consists of which four muscles?": "",
  "Supraspinatus, infraspinatus, teres minor, and subscapularis (SITS)": "",
  "Gluteus maximus, medius, minimus, and piriformis": "",
  "Pectoralis major, latissimus dorsi, serratus anterior, and rhomboid": "",
  "Deltoid, biceps, triceps, and trapezius": "",
  "The rotator cuff is composed of four muscles remembered by the mnemonic SITS (Supraspinatus, Infraspinatus, Teres minor, Subscapularis), which collectively stabilize the glenohumeral joint and enable rotation of the shoulder.": "",
  "The Achilles tendon connects which structures?": "",
  "The hamstrings to the tibia": "",
  "The gastrocnemius and soleus muscles to the calcaneus (heel bone)": "",
  "The biceps to the radius": "",
  "The quadriceps to the patella": "",
  "The Achilles tendon (calcaneal tendon) is the thickest and strongest tendon in the body, transmitting the combined force of the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles to the calcaneus bone to produce plantar flexion for walking, running, and jumping.": "",
  "Concussions in sports should be managed by:": "",
  "Ignoring the symptoms since concussions are not serious": "",
  "Removing the athlete from play and following a graduated return-to-play protocol under medical supervision": "",
  "Returning the athlete to play immediately if they feel okay": "",
  "Only administering painkillers and allowing immediate return": "",
  "Current concussion management protocols require immediate removal from play, cognitive and physical rest, medical evaluation, and a stepwise return-to-play progression where each stage must be symptom-free before advancing, to prevent second impact syndrome and long-term brain damage.": "",
  "ACL injuries are most commonly seen in which types of sports?": "",
  "Cutting and pivoting sports such as basketball, soccer, and football": "",
  "Walking, light jogging, and other low-impact linear movements": "",
  "Archery, golf, and other precision-based non-contact sports": "",
  "Swimming, cycling, and other non-weight-bearing endurance sports": "",
  "ACL injuries are most prevalent in sports requiring sudden deceleration, cutting, pivoting, and landing from jumps, such as basketball, soccer, football, and skiing, because these movements place extreme rotational and translational forces on the knee joint.": "",
  "An Achilles tendon rupture results in the inability to:": "",
  "Plantar flex the foot (push off the ground or stand on toes)": "",
  "Abduct the shoulder (lift the arm away from the body)": "",
  "Extend the hip (swing the thigh posteriorly behind you)": "",
  "Flex the knee (bend the lower leg at the knee joint)": "",
  "A ruptured Achilles tendon severs the connection between the calf muscles and the heel bone, making it impossible to plantar flex the foot with any meaningful force, severely impairing the ability to walk, run, jump, or push off the ground.": "",
  "CTE (Chronic Traumatic Encephalopathy) is associated with:": "",
  "Repeated head impacts over time, common in contact sports like football and boxing": "",
  "Muscle strains and overuse injuries in the lower back from heavy lifting": "",
  "A single isolated concussion from one traumatic head impact event": "",
  "Knee injuries from repetitive running on hard surfaces over many years": "",
  "CTE is a progressive neurodegenerative disease linked to repetitive brain trauma over years, characterized by accumulation of abnormal tau protein, and is found predominantly in athletes from contact sports like football, boxing, and hockey, causing cognitive decline, behavioral changes, and depression.": "",
  "MRI is preferred over X-ray for diagnosing sports injuries involving:": "",
  "Nothing; X-ray is always superior for all tissue types including soft structures": "",
  "Soft tissue injuries such as ligament tears, muscle damage, and cartilage injuries": "",
  "Only brain injuries, and not for any other soft tissue structures in the body": "",
  "Bone fractures only, as MRI cannot generate images of non-bony structures": "",
  "MRI (Magnetic Resonance Imaging) provides excellent contrast and detail of soft tissues including muscles, tendons, ligaments, and cartilage, making it the gold standard for diagnosing sports injuries like ACL tears, meniscus injuries, and rotator cuff tears that X-rays cannot visualize.": "",
  "Tennis elbow (lateral epicondylitis) involves:": "",
  "Inflammation of the lateral elbow tendons from repetitive wrist extension and forearm supination": "",
  "A torn rotator cuff muscle in the shoulder from repetitive overhead movements": "",
  "Inflammation of the medial collateral knee ligaments caused by repetitive lateral pivoting motions": "",
  "A stress fracture of the humerus shaft caused by repetitive throwing or swinging": "",
  "Tennis elbow is an overuse injury affecting the common extensor tendon at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus, caused by repetitive wrist extension and forearm supination movements, common in racket sports, manual labor, and computer use.": "",
  "Physical therapy after ACL reconstruction focuses on:": "",
  "Only medication management with no exercise": "",
  "Gradually rebuilding strength, range of motion, proprioception, and neuromuscular control": "",
  "Immediate return to full competition": "",
  "Complete bed rest for 6 months": "",
  "ACL rehabilitation is a structured, progressive program lasting 6-12 months that includes restoring range of motion, rebuilding quadriceps and hamstring strength, improving proprioception and balance, and gradually returning to sport-specific activities to ensure the reconstructed ligament is protected.": "",
  "What is the PCL (posterior cruciate ligament)?": "",
  "A ligament that prevents anterior tibial translation": "",
  "A ligament inside the knee that prevents posterior (backward) translation of the tibia relative to the femur": "",
  "A cartilage pad that cushions the knee joint": "",
  "A tendon connecting the quadriceps to the tibia": "",
  "The posterior cruciate ligament is a strong ligament inside the knee that prevents the tibia from sliding backward relative to the femur, working as the functional counterpart to the ACL; it is most commonly injured by a direct blow to the front of the tibia (dashboard injury).": "",
  "What is a meniscus in the knee joint?": "",
  "A C-shaped pad of fibrocartilage that cushions and stabilizes the knee joint, acting as a shock absorber": "",
  "A tendon that attaches the calf muscles to the heel": "",
  "A bone fragment within the knee joint": "",
  "A ligament that connects the femur to the tibia": "",
  "The knee contains two menisci (medial and lateral), which are C-shaped pads of fibrocartilage that sit between the femoral condyles and tibial plateau, distributing weight, absorbing shock, improving joint congruence, and providing lubrication during movement.": "",
  "What does 'proprioception' mean in sports rehabilitation?": "",
  "The body's sense of joint position, movement, and spatial orientation without visual input": "",
  "The ability to feel pain in an injured area": "",
  "The maximum force a muscle can generate": "",
  "The range of motion available at a joint": "",
  "Proprioception is the unconscious sensory ability to perceive the position, movement, and force of body parts through receptors in muscles, tendons, and joints; it is critical for balance, coordination, and preventing re-injury, and is a major focus of sports rehabilitation programs.": "",
  "What is shin splints (medial tibial stress syndrome)?": "",
  "Pain along the medial border of the tibia caused by inflammation of the periosteum and surrounding muscles from repetitive impact": "",
  "A complete fracture of the tibial shaft from a single traumatic impact rather than from repetitive stress": "",
  "A condition affecting only the forearm extensor muscles and tendons, causing pain along the lateral radius": "",
  "A ligament tear in the ankle joint, specifically the anterior talofibular ligament, caused by an inversion sprain": "",
  "Shin splints (medial tibial stress syndrome) is an overuse injury causing pain along the inner edge of the tibia, resulting from repetitive stress on the shinbone and the connective tissue attaching muscles to it, commonly seen in runners, dancers, and military recruits.": "",
  "What does 'sports medicine' encompass as a field?": "",
  "A narrow field focused solely on skeletal muscle anatomy without any clinical application, limited entirely to basic science laboratory research and textbook descriptions": "",
  "A multidisciplinary field integrating anatomy, physiology, biomechanics, nutrition, psychology, and rehabilitation for injury prevention and athletic performance": "",
  "A surgical specialty that focuses exclusively on operating on sports injuries, without any involvement in prevention, rehabilitation, nutrition, or non-surgical treatment strategies": "",
  "A field exclusively dedicated to the treatment and performance enhancement of professional athletes, with no relevance to recreational exercisers or the general population": "",
  "Sports medicine is a comprehensive, multidisciplinary field that combines knowledge of anatomy, physiology, biomechanics, exercise science, nutrition, and psychology to prevent injuries, optimize athletic performance, treat musculoskeletal conditions, and rehabilitate athletes and active individuals of all levels.": "",
  "What is the 'Thompson test' used to diagnose?": "",
  "Concussion severity, by measuring pupil dilation and reaction time after a head impact": "",
  "ACL tears in the knee, by pulling the tibia forward and assessing anterior translation": "",
  "Rotator cuff tears in the shoulder, by resisting arm abduction and checking for weakness or pain": "",
  "Achilles tendon rupture, by squeezing the calf and observing whether the foot plantar flexes": "",
  "The Thompson test (calf squeeze test) is a clinical examination where the examiner squeezes the patient's calf while the patient lies prone; if the Achilles tendon is intact, the foot will plantar flex, but if it is ruptured, the foot will not move, indicating a positive test.": "",
  "What is the SITS mnemonic?": "",
  "A mnemonic for the hamstring muscles": "",
  "A mnemonic for the four rotator cuff muscles: Supraspinatus, Infraspinatus, Teres minor, Subscapularis": "",
  "A mnemonic for the bones of the wrist": "",
  "A mnemonic for the four quadriceps muscles": "",
  "SITS is a widely used mnemonic to remember the four muscles of the rotator cuff: Supraspinatus (abduction), Infraspinatus (external rotation), Teres minor (external rotation), and Subscapularis (internal rotation), all of which stabilize the glenohumeral joint.": "",
  "What does 'return-to-play protocol' mean after a concussion?": "",
  "A stepwise progression of increasing physical activity where each stage must be completed symptom-free before advancing to the next": "",
  "Permanent removal from all sports after any concussion": "",
  "A single fitness test the day after the concussion": "",
  "Allowing the athlete to play immediately after symptoms resolve": "",
  "A return-to-play protocol is a graduated, multi-stage program (typically 6 stages from complete rest to full competition) where the athlete must remain symptom-free at each stage for at least 24 hours before progressing, designed to prevent premature return and reduce the risk of second impact syndrome.": "",
  "What does 'overuse injury' mean in sports medicine?": "",
  "An injury resulting from repetitive microtrauma that exceeds the tissue's ability to repair itself, developing gradually over time": "",
  "An injury that only occurs in professional athletes": "",
  "An injury caused by not using a muscle enough": "",
  "An injury caused by a single traumatic event like a fall or collision": "",
  "An overuse injury develops gradually when repetitive stress (from training, work, or daily activities) causes cumulative microtrauma to muscles, tendons, bones, or joints faster than the body can repair, examples including stress fractures, tendinitis, and shin splints.": "",
  "What does 'biomechanics' mean in the context of sports medicine?": "",
  "The study of the mechanical principles of movement in living organisms, including forces, levers, and motion analysis applied to human performance": "",
  "The study of nutrition for athletes, including macronutrient ratios, hydration strategies, and dietary supplementation protocols for peak performance": "",
  "The study of muscle cell biology only, focusing on the molecular structure of sarcomeres, myofilaments, and the biochemistry of contraction": "",
  "The study of how pharmacological drugs interact with skeletal muscle tissue, including performance-enhancing substances and their physiological effects": "",
  "Biomechanics is the science of applying mechanical principles to biological systems, analyzing forces, torques, and movement patterns to understand how the body moves, optimize athletic technique, design rehabilitation programs, and prevent injury through improved movement mechanics.": "",
  "A female high school soccer player lands awkwardly from a header and hears a 'pop' in her knee, followed by immediate swelling. She cannot bear weight on the leg. The team athletic trainer suspects an ACL tear. Why are female athletes statistically at higher risk for ACL injuries compared to males?": "",
  "Factors including wider pelvis (increased Q-angle), hormonal influences on ligament laxity, and neuromuscular differences in landing mechanics contribute to higher ACL injury rates in females": "",
  "Females have stronger ligaments that tear more easily under tension": "",
  "There is no actual difference in ACL injury rates between males and females": "",
  "Female athletes play more aggressive sports than males": "",
  "Female athletes are 2-8 times more likely to sustain ACL injuries due to anatomical factors (wider pelvis creating a larger Q-angle), hormonal effects (estrogen may increase ligament laxity), biomechanical differences (tendency toward knee valgus and less hamstring co-contraction when landing), and neuromuscular control patterns.": "",
  "A college baseball pitcher reports progressive shoulder pain that worsens during the late cocking and acceleration phases of throwing. MRI reveals a partial tear of the supraspinatus tendon. Why is the supraspinatus the most commonly injured rotator cuff muscle in overhead athletes?": "",
  "Only the subscapularis is ever injured in throwing athletes": "",
  "The supraspinatus is the largest and most exposed muscle in the body": "",
  "The supraspinatus is not actually part of the rotator cuff": "",
  "The supraspinatus tendon passes through the narrow subacromial space beneath the acromion, making it susceptible to impingement and repetitive microtrauma during overhead movements": "",
  "The supraspinatus tendon runs through the subacromial space (between the humeral head and acromion), where it can be compressed during overhead arm movements; repetitive throwing creates cumulative impingement and tensile stress, making the supraspinatus the most commonly torn rotator cuff muscle in overhead athletes.": "",
  "A recreational basketball player in his 40s suddenly feels a sharp pain in the back of his lower leg while sprinting, describing it as being 'kicked in the calf.' He cannot push off with that foot. The Thompson test is positive. What is the most likely diagnosis and what anatomical structure is damaged?": "",
  "A hamstring strain in the posterior thigh": "",
  "A stress fracture of the fibula": "",
  "A torn ACL, damaging the knee ligament": "",
  "An Achilles tendon rupture, severing the connection between the calf muscles and the calcaneus": "",
  "The classic presentation of an Achilles tendon rupture includes a sudden 'pop' or sensation of being kicked in the calf during explosive push-off, inability to plantar flex, and a positive Thompson test; this injury is common in middle-aged recreational athletes whose tendon has undergone age-related degeneration.": "",
  "A high school football player sustains a concussion during a game and is removed from play. His parents want him to return the following week for the championship game since he 'feels fine.' The team physician refuses. Why is premature return to play after a concussion dangerous?": "",
  "A second concussion before the brain fully heals can cause second impact syndrome, potentially fatal brain swelling, and premature return increases the risk of prolonged symptoms and long-term cognitive damage": "",
  "The physician is being overly cautious; concussions are minor injuries": "",
  "It is not dangerous; athletes routinely return after one week with no problems": "",
  "The only risk is temporary headaches that resolve on their own": "",
  "Second impact syndrome occurs when a second concussion happens before the first has fully resolved, causing catastrophic cerebral edema and potentially death; even without a second impact, returning too early can prolong recovery time, worsen symptoms, and increase the risk of long-term neurological problems.": "",
  "A marathon runner develops gradually worsening pain along the inner shin during training. X-rays are negative, but an MRI shows periosteal inflammation along the medial tibial border. The sports medicine physician diagnoses shin splints. What training modifications should be recommended?": "",
  "Surgical intervention is immediately required to repair the tibial periosteum, followed by complete restriction on weight-bearing activity for at least six months": "",
  "Increase training intensity immediately and push through the pain, as the discomfort is simply muscle weakness that will resolve with higher training loads and more frequent runs": "",
  "Reduce training volume, switch to low-impact cross-training, ensure proper footwear, gradually increase mileage, and strengthen the calf and tibialis anterior muscles": "",
  "Complete bed rest for at least three months with absolutely no exercise, as any movement will prevent the periosteum from healing and could cause a tibial stress fracture": "",
  "Shin splints management includes activity modification (reducing running volume and switching to low-impact cross-training), proper shoe fitting, gradual return to impact activities (10% rule for weekly mileage increases), and strengthening the surrounding muscles to better distribute impact forces.": "",
  "A retired professional boxer, now age 55, is experiencing memory loss, mood swings, depression, and difficulty with impulse control. His neurologist suspects CTE. The family asks if there is a definitive test to diagnose CTE while the patient is alive. What is the current status of CTE diagnosis?": "",
  "CTE can be definitively diagnosed in living patients with a simple blood test that detects elevated tau protein levels, making post-mortem brain examination completely unnecessary": "",
  "A standard MRI scan can definitively diagnose CTE in living patients by revealing characteristic patterns of tau protein deposits in the brain tissue, providing a reliable imaging biomarker": "",
  "CTE does not actually exist as a distinct medical condition and is not recognized by any major neurological organization; the symptoms attributed to CTE are better explained by normal aging processes": "",
  "Currently, CTE can only be definitively diagnosed post-mortem through brain autopsy showing characteristic tau protein accumulation; clinical diagnosis relies on symptom patterns and history of repetitive head trauma": "",
  "CTE can currently only be definitively confirmed post-mortem by neuropathological examination showing characteristic patterns of abnormal tau protein deposition; while research into biomarkers and PET imaging is advancing, clinical diagnosis in living patients is based on history of repetitive head trauma, progressive neurological symptoms, and exclusion of other conditions.": "",
  "A competitive swimmer develops shoulder pain that worsens during freestyle and butterfly strokes. The sports medicine doctor diagnoses 'swimmer's shoulder' involving rotator cuff impingement. Based on the biomechanics of swimming, why is this injury so common in competitive swimmers?": "",
  "Swimming does not actually involve repetitive shoulder movements because the water resistance and buoyancy eliminate the overhead stress that would normally occur during land-based activities": "",
  "Competitive swimmers perform thousands of overhead arm strokes per week, causing repetitive compression of the supraspinatus tendon in the subacromial space with each stroke cycle": "",
  "The chlorine and other chemical disinfectants present in pool water directly penetrate the skin and chemically degrade the collagen fibers within the shoulder tendons over time": "",
  "Swimming primarily generates mechanical stress on the hip joint and lower extremity rather than the shoulder, since the kick phase provides most of the propulsive force": "",
  "Competitive swimmers can perform 10,000-14,000 shoulder revolutions per week; each overhead stroke cycle involves impingement of the rotator cuff tendons (especially supraspinatus) in the subacromial space, and this enormous repetitive microtrauma frequently leads to tendinitis, impingement, and eventual rotator cuff tears.": "",
  "A weekend tennis player develops pain on the outside of her elbow that worsens when she grips objects or shakes hands. Her orthopedist diagnoses lateral epicondylitis (tennis elbow). She asks why this happened even though she only plays tennis once a week. What is the pathophysiology?": "",
  "Repetitive wrist extension and gripping cause micro-tears in the common extensor tendon at the lateral epicondyle, and even weekly play with poor technique or sudden increases in activity can exceed the tendon's repair capacity": "",
  "Tennis elbow is caused by a stress fracture at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus that develops from repeated impact forces transmitted through the racquet into the elbow joint during each stroke": "",
  "Tennis elbow only occurs in professional tennis players who practice many hours daily, because the tendons of recreational players are not subjected to sufficient repetitive stress to develop micro-tears": "",
  "The elbow joint partially dislocated during play, causing the common extensor tendon to sublux over the lateral epicondyle, resulting in mechanical irritation and chronic pain with gripping": "",
  "Lateral epicondylitis results from repetitive micro-tears at the origin of the wrist extensor muscles on the lateral epicondyle; factors like poor backhand technique, improper grip size, sudden increases in playing time, and insufficient recovery can overwhelm the tendon's repair capacity even with relatively infrequent play.": "",
  "An athletic trainer is implementing an ACL injury prevention program for a girls' high school soccer team. Based on sports medicine research, which components should be included in the program to reduce ACL injury risk?": "",
  "Only upper body strength training to compensate for lower body weakness": "",
  "Only static stretching before games": "",
  "Neuromuscular training including proper landing mechanics, hamstring strengthening, plyometrics, balance exercises, and core stability to improve dynamic knee control": "",
  "Wearing knee braces during all activities and avoiding all physical contact": "",
  "Evidence-based ACL prevention programs (like FIFA 11+ and PEP) include neuromuscular training to improve landing mechanics (avoiding knee valgus), hamstring strengthening to balance the quadriceps-to-hamstring ratio, plyometric drills, proprioceptive exercises, and core stability training, which can reduce ACL injuries by 50-70% in female athletes.": "",
  "A sports medicine fellow is evaluating a 17-year-old gymnast with chronic wrist pain. X-rays show a stress fracture of the distal radius. The gymnast's coach wants her to continue training for an upcoming competition. What ethical considerations should guide the physician's decision?": "",
  "The coach's wishes should override medical judgment since competition performance is most important": "",
  "Stress fractures are harmless and require no treatment modifications": "",
  "The gymnast should continue training with heavy wrist bracing to prevent further damage": "",
  "The physician must prioritize the athlete's long-term health over competition, recommend rest and modified training to allow healing, and consider the risks of continued training on a growing adolescent's bones": "",
  "Sports medicine physicians have an ethical obligation to prioritize the athlete's long-term health over competitive pressures; continuing to train on a stress fracture in an adolescent risks complete fracture, growth plate damage, and permanent deformity, and the physician should advocate for appropriate rest and modified training regardless of coaching or competitive pressure.": ""
